It is impossible, therefore, to speak with confi- dence, but most scholars will probably agree with the reviewerffi already quoted, when he maintains that Caesar would have repudiated with something like shame the scruples attributed to him. Unnatural vices no doubt he abhorred, and he was otherwise very temperate in his habits, but a Christian strictness of morals was a rare exception in those days, and his conte1np‹‘›raries do not seem to have noticed any peculiari ty of this kind in Caesar. Lord Macaulay—whose opinion on such a subject should carry great weight-would not have endorsed Mr. Froude's verdiet, if we may argue from hints afforded by his short sketch⁵⁶ of the Catilinarian movement.

Caesar then surpassed Cicero indefinitely in genius and in nerve ; but in the more distinctively Christian virtues of gentleness and domestic purity Cicero has a higher claim on our regard. The worship of Caesar in fact takes its place with Goethe-worship, and other unhealthy aber- rations, which have for their object the deification of strength or light.
